segments.text: For some people it is.
I'm sort of a garrulous kind of guy, so it doesn't
bother me to talk about it.
I enjoy telling some of the stories.
Some of them are a little tough to tell.
Some of them are, you know, I was young and foolish, so I did some things that if I had a little sense I wouldn't have done.
But I did some other things that I thought were pretty neat.
And the flare shoot's one of them.
I don't know that you want that on tape, but I'll tell you that later.
Okay.

What's your reaction to some of the, I won't say hype, but some of the, sort of for our generation, the perception that we have is mainly through movies like War on the Fourth of July, Platoon, just the Hollywood image.
What's your...
Remember the movie The Deer Hunter?
I think I have seen that.
That's a fantasy.
It has nothing to do with what happened over there at all.
What was the movie with...
I can't remember his name.
It's a guy who's a leader of indigenous troops in Cambodia or Laos or somewhere.
Marlon Brando plays the heavy...
Anyway, another fantasy, absolute fantasy.
Platoon, the guy had an axe to grind.
He had a point that he wanted to make, and he had the backing and the, you know, he was in control of the writing and direction and production and all that.
He made his point.
You try to make it sound like that kind of stuff happened all the time.
It didn't.
It did not.
You hear about...
On the 4th of July, I've been told I shouldn't see, so I didn't bother to see it.
But I've heard it's a good movie.
There's a movie called Go Tell the Spartans with Burt Lancaster that's not quite as bad as The Green Berets with John Wayne.
Although that had some accurate stuff in it.
It was also pretty hyped up.
Go Tell the Spartans was pretty accurate.
There's another one that was pretty accurate.
I can't remember what it was.
But in the movie Platoon, as much as this was this guy's perspective, he's entitled to his perspective.
There's a scene at a fire base for an LZ of some kind where it was so real that I could smell it.
Sitting in the movie theater, I could smell it, which is a...
There's some scenes, some smells, some sights and sounds you never forget.
The scene was of how they handled the cranes.
It was pretty primitive.
Basically, they used oil drums cut in half with diesel fuel, and they burned it.
To this day, when I see something like that, I can smell it.
That's one of the things we always used to say, that the language we'd use was pretty crude, but there are things that get rough over here.
You know, you think you're having a bad day, say at least you're not a Vietnamese with that job.
The movies are, in the main, they're just very narrow.
Somebody trying to...
to say here's what my experience was, and if that's real to that person, that's okay.
But it does give a distorted picture of the whole thing.
Do you think it's good that there is sort of a, I don't even say resurgence, that there is a lot of Hollywood type thing?
Well, I think they finally, they're getting a little more realistic about it.
It's just that the people pretty much take the last thing they see, and this is human nature, it's not just our culture or anything, and they scrap like that into everything goes this way.
And, you know, in college, you can even read something within the covers of a hardcover book.
And just because it's printed nicely and somebody went to the trouble to put the book together doesn't make it true.
So you have to examine...
all different sides of the question.
When you're preparing a scholarly research, you don't get it all from one volume.
That's plagiarism.
You do original research, and you get different people's points of view.
Because like I said, different people can go through the same place, same time, and come away with different perceptions.
So I think the examination is good.
I think the more that it's examined, the more people will find that me lying was an aberration.
Not a matter of policy.
We were not trained to do that.
We were told explicitly we would not kill civilians.
You hear about the inflated body counts?
Yeah.
May have occurred, okay?
Where I operated, you didn't count, confirm, kill, unless somebody could touch the body.
Sort of like counting coup.
We did not inflate body count.
And I guarantee that.
I know that for a fact.
I was at the reports sessions where the reports went forward.
Do you think that was a lot different?
Because that is something that you do here.
Do you think that was different from another section, say, the ground?
Could have been.
But I do know that, remember I told you how few Americans were killed in the year I was there where I was?
When we got body count of Vietnamese, of North Vietnamese, we got a lot, especially working with the works.
We got 50 and 75 and 100 at a time.
And one day, I got eight in one place.
And I thought, boy, the war's really going on right here where I was.
And province-wide that day, we got 400.
And you could touch each body.
A friend of mine got shot down after six months in country and had a journalism degree and was tagged to be on the Typhoon, the newspaper for two corps.
And, or not, it's a magazine.
So he got called out to every big action to report it to the Typhoon magazine.
And he went out to one deal one time where
There were so many bodies.
You've heard the expression, you could walk across a field without stepping on the ground.
You could walk across a field without stepping on the ground.
He saw that with his own eyes.
You didn't have to exaggerate.
Anybody that exaggerates has got a personality defect because the stuff that happened was incredible enough without having to exaggerate.
Little Bobby Beal was shot down one day.
He took 17 rounds in the aircraft.
One of them

came up through the floor between his captain, Army captain in the back seat's feet, passed through the back of Bob's seat between his arm and his body, glanced off the map case that he was resting his arm on, which was attached to the door, and went up to the top of the windshield.
Didn't touch anybody.
17 rounds, nobody hit.
One round goes to an intake manifold, which cuts the power, makes the plane incapable of sustaining flight because they're so heavy.
He was in the mountains.
He was at 5,000 feet.
He had time to glide down out of the mountains to an old abandoned French overgrown strip that has cows grazing on it.
He's calling for help.
By the time he gets down, there's so many aircraft waiting to help him, there's a traffic jam.
There's more danger of mid-air collisions than there is enemy.
And he builds up speed and buzzes the strip to run the cows off and then uses that excess speed to turn around and come in and land.
Hits a cow
with the gear, bounces off the cow, and lands.
No damage to the aircraft other than the 17 holes.
And they later on decided, well, in the next 10 years, somebody else might want to use this strip, so let's repair it and grade it.
And the Army didn't do anything, anything, over there without checking for mines first on roads or strips or anything like that.
They found five old mines that the cows had been grazing around and all that.
He didn't hit, the cows didn't hit, nobody hit.
So, I mean, weird things like that.
My flare shoot was a weird deal.
And you don't have to exaggerate.
In a book we had to read for this class, Things That Carry, by Tim O'Brien, one of the interesting things that he says is every war story really doesn't have an end.
Do you feel that that is true?
Every war story doesn't have an end?
What does he mean by that?
Sort of, um...

But it doesn't really always have an ending, but it kind of... Well... Do you feel like that for you, or do you think it's something you live with now, or do you feel like it's something that's passed?
Oh, I see what you're saying.
No, I think I still am affected by some of it.
You know, some World War II veterans had it much rougher than anybody in Vietnam almost.
POWs in Vietnam had it as rough as anybody.
Which, by the way, was another thing that really set us off, was the way the POWs were treated, and the way some of our high-profile people, Jane Fonda, I will see a movie with Jane Fonda in it.
I won't give her a dime of my money in any way, shape, or form.
She is not apologetic for what she did.
Clark Clifford, was it?
No, who was it?
Who was the other guy that went over there?
former attorney general.
Anyway, people like that, the people who were protesting the war may have been cowards, may have had conviction, I don't know.
But people who went over there and consorted with the enemy ought not to be citizens of this country, period.
And Jane Fonda's right up there.
I mean, she sat behind an anti-aircraft gun
aiming, you know, showing being filmed or having her picture taken as if she was aiming at U.S. planes.
And she celebrated the U.S. planes being shot down.
Now, that woman can rot in hell as far as I'm concerned.
I don't think a lot of my generation knows.
I think that they're really unaware.
What...
I think that there is so much literature and so much scholarly research after so many of the other words.
And I feel like this war, not so much that it was secretive, but there's not a lot of scholarly or... Well, it was such a black period in our history that at first it was shoved under the table.
People wanted to ignore it.
Then when it came out that people were going to write more about it and
have sort of a catharsis.
A lot of the writings were from a point of view.
They weren't really historical presentations, trying to be as accurate in reading the reports and getting into as much actual detail as possible.
But rather, here's my point of view, and I'm going to write about this, and that's the way it was.
Fields of Fire by James Webb, have you read that?
One of the toughest books to read.
Tough book to read.
But as far as what he wrote about that I personally knew and that everybody that I knew that served over there that read it personally knew, it was 100% accurate.
100% accurate.
I mean, tough book.

And yet he may have been writing from his point of view and in your mind sometimes you remember things maybe a little more than what occurred or a little less than what occurred or a little differently than what occurred.
I think I remember it pretty accurately, but
I may not.
Somebody else who was there with me might say, oh, no, John, that didn't happen that way.
Same thing happens when my fraternity brothers and I get together and talk about our college days.
And we've got some great stories there, too, but we remember them differently.
Another book, I bought this book, and it's called Charlie Mike.
And Charlie Mike is what, you know, the phonetic alphabet, Charlie stands for C and Mike stands for M.
And we would use things like that in lieu of whole words or ideas.
And Charlie Mike means continue to march.
And when you're working with the lurks, they would call in on the radio and they'd whisper because they were afraid of getting heard by the enemy.
And they'd describe what they'd heard.
And you could tell by the pitch of their voice when they're really scared.
The pitch gets higher.
You can hear it.
I could still hear it.
And usually they'd get scared before there was anything really to be scared about.

And the lieutenant in the back seat, or the captain in the back seat, who was controlling this suite, this operation, would hear what they had to say, and as often as not, he'd say, Charlie, Mike, please continue to march.
They'd travel during the day, and then about 4 in the afternoon,
They'd try to make sure they hadn't been observed and find a place to park for the night and stay there until after sun up the next morning and start moving out again.
These guys, I mean, that was dangerous work.
That was tough, tough stuff.
They had to carry everything they needed.
Water, which is the heaviest thing.
They always carried more ammunition than they were authorized to carry and more weapons.
They were incredibly strong guys.
They'd go out all painted up,
in broad daylight, and it's scary to run over one of them.
And they'd go out there and look for these guys, and occasionally get in firefights, just them and a whole herd of North Vietnamese.
And it was tough duty.
But this book was about, written by a major who had been in Charlie Company's 75th Rangers.
And he described three incidents in that book
that occurred in my province while I was there, two of which involved me.
And you could definitely relate.
And I picked the book up on a whim and had one of those covers with a guy with bandoliers of ammunition across his chest, you know, and I thought, God, what a hokey book this is going to be.
And it was.
But he related things in that book that I myself had observed after a fashion afternoon.
He talked about one part in the book where these guys are running through the jungle.
with the North Vietnamese chasing them.
Well, I had a team get jumped by a bunch of North Vietnamese and we had moved an artillery battery out.
We blasted the mountaintop to clear the trees off and created a fire base and moved some 105 howitzers out there by helicopter.
And so I was calling 105 fire in between
the work team and the North Vietnamese trying to keep the North Vietnamese off their backs so they could get to an LZ to get extracted.
And I couldn't see anybody.
And these guys, the lurks, would tell me where my fire was coming by the shrapnel coming through the trees.
And they'd say, you're getting too close.
And I walked artillery behind them all the way to the LZ, and they got out.
But an incident like that was in the book, which I thought was fascinating.
We enjoyed working with the lurks.
That was good.
The communication was good.
The communication was good.
We had good relations with them.
They did a good job and we got, we had a lot of success.
Did you hear any stories from them or anything else about the tunnels or any?
The bunkers?
The tunnel rats, we never, I never experienced any tunnel rats in my area.
You know, the GIs would go down in the tunnels, and that's scary stuff.
I'm a little claustrophobic.
I don't think I would have liked that at all.
But they had, you know, the communists would put punji stakes in the tunnels, and they would put snakes and booby traps of all kinds.
And that's not my idea of a good time.
I'm glad I was a pilot.
Another thing in that book...
that I thought was really interesting was, he said it was a war without rules.
It wasn't like a checkerboard where, one of the analogies, he said it wasn't like a checkerboard where they move, you move.
It was without rules.
Do you think that the United States was playing it like it had rules and the enemy wasn't?
I feel that way very strongly.
Like I said, we avoided civilian casualties as much as we could.
Even when we bombed the North, we did everything we could to avoid civilian casualties.
It's going to happen in any war.
Friendly fire is going to happen in any war.
We did our best to avoid it.
We did play by the rules.
You should not have those kind of rules.
You should not give your enemy a sanctuary.
We didn't have front line that we could if they mixed with the civilian population.
I was up one night, and I was asked to put artillery, 8-inch artillery, into a village.
And I said, that's a civilian village.
I mean, there's civilians in there.
I'm not going to fire in there.
And they said, no, the civilians have been pulled out the day before.
You're cleared to fire.
And I said, are you sure?
And he said, not only am I sure, but if you look, you're taking tracers off for 6 o'clock, green and white tracers.
The enemy used green and white tracers instead of red.
So once I had that assurance, I put artillery in the village.
But we sweated and sprained to make sure that there weren't any civilians in there.
The Koreans who fought with us in Vietnam didn't care.
If they took fire from a village, they'd say, we did it.
And if they didn't,
tell them they'd line up their tanks, hub to hub, and drive over the village.
The people better get out of the way.
So yeah, we fought by rules, and war's a tough thing to...
I mean, you've got to have some rules or you're not a human being anymore.
But as far as sanctuary, that's silly.
And the communists would use civilians.
There was a...
I called Ann one time
And then I asked her about it again when I went to Hawaii to see her.
A bus with nothing on it but civilians was blown up by a command detonated mine.
Now that means that somebody has to punch the trigger.
It's not one that you just run over and it goes off.
They found the wires and everything.
The communists blew up that bus to show that they controlled the road.
They knew who they were killing.
They did it as a matter of policy.
We didn't do that.
I asked Ann.
I bet you that made the papers in the States, didn't it?
She never heard of it.
Didn't make the papers in the States.
Communists doing atrocities, which they did all the time as a matter of policy, the press didn't care about that.
Just what the United States did.
And if the United States screws up, the press is supposed to point it out.
I'm not saying they shouldn't.
They shouldn't make it sound like we do it all the time, and they shouldn't ignore the fact that the enemy does it.
That's one-sided.
How many memories are acknowledged today?
Talk about the Ho Chi Minh Trail, controlling the road.
The Ho Chi Minh Trail was a sign of how incredibly disciplined
the North Vietnamese were.
They took trucks, but not only trucks, but bicycles and packs.
It was like an army of ants going down this trail.
We bombed the trail and they just moved around where we bombed.
It was an incredible back and forth game.
We did have a Chu Hoi in our province who, when asked why he surrendered, he said, well, it's like this.
He says, I was in
North Vietnamese, minding my own business.
I get drafted into the Army.
And he says, you know, all these guys are going south and none of them are coming back, so I'm pretty scared.
But I'm given a load to take down the Ho Chi Minh Trail on the back.
And he's a bunch of mortar rounds.
And they would start this trail all the way down from North Vietnam carrying ammunition, and the fingers went out to all over South Vietnam.
So his finger happened to go down into my province, Binh Duan Province.
He says, I get down here.
I'm months on this trail.
I'm getting bombed.
I'm getting rained on.
It's miserable.
I get down here.
I say, here I am, and here's my mortar round.
And the guy says, all right, great.
Come on down here.
And I go down this trail.
The guy sets up a mortar tube, takes my rounds, fires them off, says, let's get out of here.
We get out.
He says, now go get some more.
He says, that's not what I want to do.
So he surrendered.
He says, all I'm going to do is be a pack mule.
I'm going to give up.
But people gave up for different reasons.
I will tell you, we killed a lot of Vietnamese.
We killed a lot of North Vietnamese.
When I first got there, they could not mount a serious offensive.
Remember, I got there in May of 69.
A year and five months or four months after Tet of 68, they could still not mount a serious effort because they were so decimated by Tet of 68.
After I'd been there about six months, they were getting major North Vietnamese units in my province.
And we killed a lot of them.
How did you feel about, or how did people feel about the age?
I know that they made a lot of children fight.
How did they feel about it?
Did they want to?
The communists ruled by fear.
They made up a policy of killing the village leaders and the teachers, the educated people.
This is documented.
They would take them out and kill them in front of the rest of the village.
and say, if you don't do what we say, this will happen to you.
Anybody that resisted them was shot in front of the rest of the village as a lesson.
They scared most of these people into serving with them.
It wasn't that they were all that dedicated.
A lot of them were scared, and they'd get killed if they didn't serve, so why not go ahead and fight and have a chance of living than not do what they say and get killed.
So that was common practice.
practice.
Quite often they'd get children who really didn't know any better to throw a grenade or something like that.
And because we were so conscious of not killing civilians, a lot of GIs got killed because they hesitated, even though they saw a girl or a child carrying a weapon.
They'd hesitate just long enough
For them to get killed.
That's a lot of the pictures you see.
Yeah, a lot.
So, you know, sometimes GIs got a little trigger happy after they've been shot at a few times by civilians.
Or you'd see a civilian walking down a road and they'd walk like this, do a little movement around a certain spot, and they knew the mine was there.
And they wouldn't tell the GIs, hey, there's a mine there.
They'd just let them
run over it.
If you ever saw any civilian doing that, you immediately changed your mind.
Anyway.
Did you, um, what was probably the scariest moment?
Well, the night in the mountains.
I had no artificial horizon.
It was inoperative.
Had no radio waves navigation.
You could tell where I was.
My team was lost and in trouble.
We flew into the valley, and the clouds were below the mountaintops.
And you could tell the mountains from the clouds because the mountains were a little blacker.
And the ranger in my back seat said, I think they're over this direction.
And he had me flying up a little finger of the valley that the sides were closing in.
And you get to a point where you can't turn around and get out without running into them.
We just had a couple of helicopters hit the mountains and kill everybody on board recently.
And so I was getting a little antsy, and I said, you know, A, I don't think they're over here, and B, I'm not flying up this valley anymore.
And we found them 11 kilometers away and told them where they were and made sure the radio contact was established and everything was okay.
And like I said, I would fly in and out of clouds, and all I had to orient myself was my altimeter and my airspeed indicator and my turn-and-back indicator.
And I can't tell you today how I got out of there.
Ann asked me one time, what was the scariest thing that ever happened?
Was it the flare shoot?
And I said, no, it was the night in the mountains.
And I got all teary because I just don't know how I got out of there.
But the flare shoot was pretty interesting.
was firing a Stinger gunship, which is an Air Force C-119 with 20mm Vulcan Gatling guns on.
A compound of RFPF, Regional Force Popular Force, like a militia compound, had been hit.
It was right on QL1, which is the main highway that runs north-south through Vietnam, or at this point it ran east-west because of the way the country is organized or outlined.
And so, to the south,
from this stretch of the road was the ocean, and they wouldn't try to get out there because they're too easily spotted.
To the north were these stream beds that led up to the mountains to the Triple Canopy Jungle, and that's the way they would logically go.
So I was flying at about 1,000 feet above the ground.
The gunship was flying at 4,000 feet above the ground, and he was kicking flares out.
I was flying in a racetrack south of the highway, and he was flying north of the highway in a racetrack.
And I could see the ground, and I could actually adjust his fire into these screen beds.
And I don't know if we got anybody, but that's the only thing you can do.
Well, a dust-off helicopter, medical evacuation helicopter, came into the compound to pick up the wounded, and on another frequency asked for another flare.
So unbeknownst to me, as I'm looking down at the ground, this guy flies, does a little jog, and kicks out another flare over the compound.
So I'm flying heading east and looking out to the right at the ground north of the highway.
And I look up and come to see a white blur in front of my nose.
And what had happened was this flare had burned out.
All the flares were burning out above my altitude.
But as long as they were north of the highway, the wind was blowing them to the west.
I'm sorry, the wind was blowing them to the east.
I was flying west.
They were out of my way.
But on this one, it was right in front of me.
And it was one of those instant recognition things.
I knew what it was.
And I jammed rudder and aileron and turned my head like this, sort of like a flinch when you know you're going to hit something.
And if it had hit my prop, it would have been all over.
But it hit my left wing.
And the way these things are, they're a...
16-foot diameter canopy parachute with shroud lines go down to a ring with a quarter-inch thick steel cable from which hangs a big canister, rubberized canister that burns.
And that's what creates this flare.
And so I went like this, and apparently what happened was the thing went over the top of the wing that the parachute did, and
ballooned or like a big air brake, and it snapped me to the left.

At the same time, I heard this loud wham, and that was a canister swinging up underneath it, hitting the underside of the wing and left a dent about that, about three inches deep under the underside of the wing.
And when I snapped to the left, I thought I'd lost a wing.
And I jammed more rudder and looked over and saw that what I had was this big air brake.
So I got it by holding all the rudder I could.
My right leg was
working like mad, I got it flying straight.
And it slowed me down from my normal 90 knots to 70.
And yet at that speed, it's like...
